  "exemplar_id": "ex_sle_screen_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "30-year-old woman presenting with a few days of dysuria and increased urinary frequency on a background of chronic overactive bladder (treated with intravesical Botox twice yearly) and recurrent UTIs (last one 3 months ago). She is not sexually active, last period 2 weeks ago, denies flank pain or vaginal symptoms. She has just mentioned feeling tired and 'a little hot,' and added — when asked about any facial changes — that her mother commented she looked 'a little flushed' today.",
  "good_next_question": "No markings across the bridge of your nose and your cheeks?",
  "rationale": "This question is a deliberate pivot away from the obvious UTI track to screen for systemic lupus erythematosus — a diagnosis a novice would not even consider in someone presenting with dysuria. The trigger is the pattern: a young woman with recurrent infections (lupus nephritis can cause recurrent sterile pyuria mistaken for UTI), fatigue, subjective fever, and now facial flushing observed by family. The malar (butterfly) rash sparing the nasolabial folds is one of the most specific clinical criteria for SLE. A positive answer would dramatically reorder the differential — converting a routine UTI visit into a workup for autoimmune disease with urinalysis for casts/proteinuria, ANA, complement, and dsDNA. A negative answer keeps lupus in the differential without anchoring on it but justifies the broader workup the doctor will pursue. This question beats simply documenting 'rash: no' because the specific anatomic distribution is what makes it diagnostic — flushing alone is non-specific, malar distribution is not.",
  "tags": [
    "urinary",
    "young_female",
    "autoimmune",
    "atypical_features",
    "pattern_recognition",
    "sle",
    "red_flag_screening"
  ],
